description: net (“elegant, neat”) +‎ -y (“forming adjs. of slightly lesser degree”)

examples: How prettie, how fine and how nettie,Good huswife should yettie.

entries.meaning: Netted: made of or employing a net.
examples: Ye ought for to keepe them close, till the day haue taken the gellie or netty rime, from the earth.

description: Uncertain. Proposed derivations include a corruption of necessary, a euphemism for outhouse; French nettoyer (“to cleanse”); and Italian gabinetto (“toilet”).

entries.meaning: (Tyneside) An outhouse: an outbuilding used as a lavatory.
examples: A line of pit cottages... tiny back gardens with outside lavatories, ‘netties’, some of them emptied twice a week by the council.

entries.meaning: (Tyneside) Any other place or fixture used for urination and defecation: a lavatory; a toilet.
examples: Netty, a privy or water-closet... A common name, amongst the working classes... In common use. In my recollection it was looked upon as a euphemism.
